{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":169803,"duration_api_ms":169730,"ttft_ms":110479,"num_turns":1,"result":"I'll produce one structured idea record. This run is in Critique mode on the \"remainder pressure after self-negation\" frontier, which is dense with near-neighbor rubrics, so the honest move is to narrow the frontier's central testable claim rather than add another support map. (Note: I am not invoking multi-agent orchestration here; the task is to return a single idea record, and a workflow would be wasteful and inappropriate for that.)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The Book Cannot Tell You What Will Hold You\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. The active frontier claims that coders who see only doctrinal negation passages can predict above baseline where later manuals place support. This run pressures that exact claim.\",\n    \"Thinking-method source: the temperament-diagnosis method of Buddhaghosa's Visuddhimagga, where the teacher first reads the practitioner's character before prescribing a meditation support. I used it as a lens by refusing to ask what a doctrine implies and instead asking what this particular person needs. Self-critique of the method: temperament typing can stereotype, can harden into a rigid six-type scheme, and presumes a trustworthy diagnostician, so it was checked against Daoist non-forcing, which warns against imposing any single map.\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison: Visuddhimagga III assigns different supports for the same liberation by temperament (foulness contemplation for the greedy character, loving-kindness for the hating character, breath and element analysis for the discursive), while Shinran's Tannisho relocates all support uniformly to the vow and treats per-person calculation as self-power error. The comparison reveals that support placement is per-person in one tradition and deliberately fixed-for-all in the other, so doctrine about the self does not by itself determine where continuity is held.\",\n    \"Cross-index with prior cluster work on continuity placement, custody, receiving surface, support-holder loss, and the question-fit and over-rubric critiques; this record narrows their shared assumption that placement is a doctrinal constant.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition grounding: U.S. Surgeon General advisory on loneliness and social connection; Pew on where Americans find meaning. The affected wound is isolated seekers deriving life-altering instructions from texts and apps rather than from a relationship that can read their particular fragility.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"When a practice loosens the ordinary self, the question of what then holds a person together, attention, body, a teacher, a vow, a duty, a community, has usually been answered not by the tradition's teaching about the self but by a live read of the particular practitioner. The same goal of self-release is matched to different supports for a grasping temperament, an anxious one, or a doubting one. This means a self-negating doctrine under-determines where continuity is placed: placement is largely a pedagogical decision keyed to a person's makeup and current fragility, not a fact you can read off the doctrine. The practical consequence is sharp: trying to learn from a text alone what will steady you after you let go is using the wrong source, because the text was never the place the support was assigned.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Much recent work treats where support is held as a property of a path that can be coded from its negation passages. This reverses that: support placement is mostly a per-person clinical judgment, so doctrine-only coding should fail to predict it. The contribution is not another map of possible supports but a claim about which source carries the placement information, with a clean falsification: strip the temperament-matching texts, give coders only the negation doctrine, and their prediction of where manuals place support should collapse toward chance.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The strongest counterexample is radical Other Power. Shinran does not place support per temperament; he fixes it uniformly in the vow precisely because trusting the practitioner's makeup would reintroduce self-power. If many mature traditions converge on one uniform support for everyone, then doctrine does predict placement after all, and my claim holds only for effort and insight paths that retain a diagnostic teacher. A second weakness: temperament matching may be a late commentarial overlay (Buddhaghosa systematizing) rather than how placement actually happened, so the per-person pattern could be an artifact of one scholastic text. The claim should be weakened if placement turns out to be set by institution, ritual form, or lineage default rather than by a read of the individual.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\"textual\", \"interpretive\", \"empirical-adjacent\", \"analogical\", \"speculative\"],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.54,\n    \"generativity\": 0.8,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.66,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.82,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.76,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.6,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.8,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.7,\n    \"publishability\": 0.6\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then coders given only self-negation doctrine, with temperament-matching and pedagogical texts removed, should predict where manuals place support no better than a teacher-interview baseline. If doctrine alone predicts placement robustly across traditions, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"If placement is per-person, then within a single tradition two practitioners pursuing the same self-release should be assigned different supports keyed to character; if assignment is uniform within traditions and varies only between them, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"Test radical Other Power as the boundary case: does any effort or insight tradition also fix one support for all, or is uniform placement unique to grace traditions that deny self-power?\",\n    \"Compare against aptitude-treatment-interaction research in psychotherapy: does matching support to a client's profile outperform the modality's general theory at predicting what stabilizes a person? If matching adds nothing beyond the modality, the analogy weakens.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before asking what a tradition says remains after negation, first ask who, in that tradition, decides what will hold this particular student, and whether that decision is written down at all.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The Book Cannot Tell You What Will Hold You\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"What steadies you when the self loosens is chosen for your particular makeup, not read off a page.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"After a practice that weakens ordinary self-command, where your steadiness is placed, in attention, the body, a duty, a person, a vow, depends on your specific temperament and current fragility, not on what the teaching says about the self.\",\n    \"body\": \"You can read a hundred descriptions of letting go and still not know what will catch you when you do. That is not a gap in the books. The books were never where the answer lived. A good guide watches the particular person first: the one who grasps is given one footing, the one who fears is given another, the one who doubts is given a third, even when the aim is the same. So before you take up a practice that loosens who you are, do not ask the text what remains. Ask what has actually held you before, and find someone who can see your particular weight. Let go only as fast as something real can carry you.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Meaning-seeking isolation: self-guided seekers who trust texts and apps over relationships and try to derive from reading what only a live read of their character could supply.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Isolated self-directed practitioners, app meditators, and achievement-driven readers who reach for self-dissolving practices alone and over-intellectualize what should steady them.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survives the primary-text contrast between the Visuddhimagga assigning different supports by temperament and Shinran's uniform placement of all support in the vow, by claiming per-person placement for effort and insight paths while naming radical Other Power as the deliberate exception.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if support placement turns out to be uniform within traditions and predictable from doctrine alone, if it is set by institution or ritual default rather than a read of the individual, or if uniform grace-style placement generalizes beyond Pure Land.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\"self-release\", \"support-placement\", \"temperament\", \"loneliness\", \"self-guided-practice\", \"critique-mode\"]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Name What Has Held You Before You Loosen the Self\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"Before taking up a self-dissolving practice, name your own makeup and what has actually steadied you.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To stop a person from deriving their steadiness from a text and to relocate the question to their own history and to someone who can read their particular fragility.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Isolation and over-intellectualizing among self-guided seekers who adopt destabilizing practices from books or apps without knowing what will hold them.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Stable, self-directed readers and app meditators drawn to self-inquiry, surrender, or no-self practices on their own.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for people in coercive teacher or guru situations, where trusting another to place your support is the danger; not for acute crisis, psychosis, mania, dissociation, severe depression, or addiction withdrawal, where clinical care and direct support come first; not needed for people already working with a trustworthy guide who reads them well.\",\n    \"duration\": \"12 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Once before adopting a new self-loosening practice, and again if the practice starts to destabilize you.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Complete it fully once, with the relationship step, before judging it.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Name your strongest lean in plain words: do you tend to grasp and over-control, to fear and brace, to doubt and circle, or to go numb and drift.\",\n      \"Recall one real time you were genuinely destabilized, by loss, exhaustion, or fear, and write down what actually restored you, not what should have.\",\n      \"Treat that real thing, a person, a routine, the body, a duty, a place, as your first support candidate, ahead of the one the practice assumes.\",\n      \"Name one person who can see your particular weight, and tell them you are starting this practice and may need them.\",\n      \"Decide one limit in advance: how far you will loosen before you check in with that person or stop.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether your real past support matches or conflicts with what the practice assumes will hold you.\",\n      \"Whether naming a person lowers the urge to do this entirely alone.\",\n      \"Whether you are reaching for a text to answer a question only a relationship can answer.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Stop if the practice destabilizes you faster than your named support can carry, or if it increases isolation, shame, or dependency on an unsafe authority. This is not a substitute for therapy, medical care, or crisis support.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It weakens if people cannot name any past support, if naming a person increases shame or avoidance, or if it makes no difference compared with simply pacing the practice slowly with ordinary social contact.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\"pre-practice\", \"support-placement\", \"temperament\", \"low-risk\", \"self-guided\", \"relationship\"]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Near-Neighbor Search on Per-Person Placement\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"If the contribution is real, prior work will cover upaya, temperament-matched meditation, and lists of possible supports, but will not already state that self-negation doctrine under-determines support placement because placement is a per-person pedagogical decision that defeats doctrine-only prediction. If that exact claim exists, novelty should fall below 0.35.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Read Visuddhimagga III on carita, upaya scholarship, Pargament religious coping, aptitude-treatment-interaction literature, and the prior continuity and custody records, looking for the placement-source claim specifically.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Doctrine-Only Placement Prediction\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Coders given only self-negation doctrine, with temperament-matching and pedagogical passages removed, will not predict where manuals place support better than a teacher-interview baseline. If doctrine-only coders match or beat the baseline, the model is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Build a corpus separating negation doctrine from temperament-matching instruction across Theravada insight, Advaita self-inquiry, Soto Zen, Dzogchen, and Pure Land, then run blind placement-prediction coding.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Treatment-Matching Cross-Domain Check\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"In psychotherapy, matching a destabilizing practice to a client's profile should predict what stabilizes them better than the modality's general theory, mirroring per-person support placement. If client matching adds nothing beyond the modality, the analogy and the model both weaken.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Review aptitude-treatment-interaction and personalized-medicine findings for exposure and acceptance-based therapies, coding whether per-client matching outperforms modality-level prescription.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"281d47e2-cddb-4599-ae03-4d04cf858cef","total_cost_usd":2.2898722499999997,"usage":{"input_tokens":3772,"cache_creation_input_tokens":321381,"cache_read_input_tokens":16812,"output_tokens":10159,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":321381,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":3772,"output_tokens":10159,"cache_read_input_tokens":16812,"cache_creation_input_tokens":321381,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":321381},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-8":{"inputTokens":3772,"outputTokens":10159,"cacheReadInputTokens":16812,"cacheCreationInputTokens":321381,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":2.2898722499999997,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"5d9d5c7b-8a19-41cb-a527-94b50e700272"}
